movies that I've ever seen.

00:46:17.910 --> 00:46:18.850
Thank you.

00:46:18.850 --> 00:46:23.050
But my question was
sort of, I guess,

00:46:23.050 --> 00:46:28.710
related to that, in that
you have, with that being

00:46:28.710 --> 00:46:32.425
a major exception, you have
these two parallel trajectories

00:46:32.425 --> 00:46:38.170
as being like an actor in
films and like a playwright.

00:46:38.170 --> 00:46:40.090
[INAUDIBLE] writing for theater.

00:46:40.090 --> 00:46:43.170
You haven't done much
writing for film, right?

00:46:43.170 --> 00:46:48.090
And I was kind of curious if
that was something you ever

00:46:48.090 --> 00:46:49.920
intended to explore,
being involved

00:46:49.920 --> 00:46:55.872
in the world of movies,
and whether maybe

00:46:55.872 --> 00:46:57.455
the primary reason
you haven't done so

00:46:57.455 --> 00:47:00.540
is more related to the
form of the theater

00:47:00.540 --> 00:47:02.977
or different expectations
of the audiences?

00:47:02.977 --> 00:47:05.310
I just wondered if you could
speak to that a little bit.

00:47:05.310 --> 00:47:10.140
WALLACE SHAWN: Well, this play
is does include quite a bit

00:47:10.140 --> 00:47:19.310
about show business that is
based on my having hung around

00:47:19.310 --> 00:47:22.210
in the movie and TV world.

00:47:22.210 --> 00:47:27.610
There's quite a bit in the play
that reflects that, really.

00:47:32.210 --> 00:47:39.190
I mean, the theater, and
movies, it is a very different--

00:47:39.190 --> 00:47:42.190
well, I'm not in movies anymore,
because nobody would hire me.

00:47:42.190 --> 00:47:44.950
But I'm occasionally
in television.

00:47:52.190 --> 00:47:54.200
It's a different universe,
because people are

00:47:54.200 --> 00:47:59.380
being paid to be on television.

00:47:59.380 --> 00:48:06.540
And it's saying, I don't know.

00:48:06.540 --> 00:48:09.110
People walk into the room
with a smile on their face

00:48:09.110 --> 00:48:11.390
and a certain sense
because of that check

00:48:11.390 --> 00:48:12.350
that they've received.

00:48:16.100 --> 00:48:18.650
There's a fundamental
seriousness to theater

00:48:18.650 --> 00:48:21.690
because people are
not paid, I suppose.

00:48:21.690 --> 00:48:23.530
ANNAPURNA SRIRAM: No, we're not.

00:48:23.530 --> 00:48:26.780
SCOTT ELLIOT: But your writing
is like, "My Dinner with Andre"

00:48:26.780 --> 00:48:28.307
could be a play.

00:48:28.307 --> 00:48:30.140
You know, because it's
so written, you know.

00:48:30.140 --> 00:48:32.870
It has like-- the
writing is so gorgeous.

00:48:32.870 --> 00:48:36.620
And in movies,
the image drives--

00:48:36.620 --> 00:48:38.900
I mean the writing and
the image drive it.

00:48:38.900 --> 00:48:42.570
And I think it's so
hard to write a play.

00:48:42.570 --> 00:48:45.560
It's the hardest, I
think, to write, I think.

00:48:45.560 --> 00:48:49.550
Writing movies is--
there are programs

00:48:49.550 --> 00:48:51.530
that can help you through that.

00:48:51.530 --> 00:48:55.040
But writing a play,
you have to have

00:48:55.040 --> 00:49:00.470
the skill of being able to get
everything across in the words,

00:49:00.470 --> 00:49:02.360
and I think it's hard.

00:49:02.360 --> 00:49:04.090
I think it's harder
than writing a novel.

00:49:04.090 --> 00:49:05.756
Or I mean, I've never
even attempted it,

00:49:05.756 --> 00:49:07.850
because I find it
so intimidating.

00:49:07.850 --> 00:49:10.327
But I have dashed off a
couple of screen things,

00:49:10.327 --> 00:49:10.910
I have to say.

00:49:10.910 --> 00:49:14.180
So it's a little bit easier.

00:49:14.180 --> 00:49:17.600
And also, movies are very
collaborative in that way.

00:49:17.600 --> 00:49:20.540
And plays are very,
very, very much

00:49:20.540 --> 00:49:23.450
about what the
playwright is saying

00:49:23.450 --> 00:49:25.160
and what the
playwright has written.

00:49:25.160 --> 00:49:28.635
In movies, they throw out the
scene if they feel like it.

00:49:28.635 --> 00:49:30.272
SPEAKER 1: And if
you do it badly,

00:49:30.272 --> 00:49:31.730
you do it again or
change the line.

00:49:31.730 --> 00:49:33.020
SCOTT ELLIOT: Exactly.

00:49:33.020 --> 00:49:34.110
You can cut around it.

00:49:34.110 --> 00:49:35.150
MATTHEW BRODERICK: Have
you ever written things

00:49:35.150 --> 00:49:36.620
directly for the screen?

00:49:39.750 --> 00:49:41.600
WALLACE SHAWN: No, no.

00:49:41.600 --> 00:49:50.160
I've just-- I'm too afraid
